{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646460"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:31:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:31:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.1,0.76,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79259"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10898"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64593"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7235"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25340"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27132"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79259"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe obturator nerve arises from the lumbar plexus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of this nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Innervation of the anterior compartment of the thigh","Innervation of the lateral compartment of the thigh","Innervation of the medial compartment of the thigh","Innervation of the gluteal region","Innervation of the posterior compartment of the thigh"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe obturator nerve is primarily responsible for the innervation of the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial compartment of the thigh\u003C/strong\u003E. It facilitates the adduction of the thigh by innervating muscles such as the adductor longus, adductor brevis, and part of the adductor magnus. Additionally, it provides sensory innervation to the skin of the medial thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInnervation of the anterior compartment of the thigh\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the function of the femoral nerve, which supplies muscles such as the quadriceps femoris.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInnervation of the posterior compartment of the thigh\u003C/strong\u003E is mainly the function of the sciatic nerve, which supplies muscles like the hamstrings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInnervation of the lateral compartment of the thigh\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised anatomical compartment in terms of nerve supply, as the lateral thigh is primarily associated with the iliotibial band and tensor fasciae latae, which are innervated by the superior gluteal nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInnervation of the gluteal region\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the function of the superior and inferior gluteal nerves, which supply muscles such as the gluteus maximus, medius, and minimus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The obturator nerve is responsible for the innervation of the medial compartment of the thigh, primarily facilitating adduction of the thigh.","The obturator nerve also provides sensory innervation to the skin of the medial thigh."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, 